10:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. Canva is best suited for non designers, social media managers, small businesses, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Framer, meanwhile, shines for designers, startups, portfolio sites, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2012, Canva describes itself as \"All-in-one visual design platform with AI-powered creation tools.\" Framer, established in 2013, positions itself as \"AI-powered website builder with professional design and CMS capabilities.\" Both platforms have been in the market for a similar duration, giving each ample time to refine their offerings and build a loyal user base."}]]}]
11:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Canva** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to higher user ratings (9.0 vs 8.0), more features (10 vs 9), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean Framer is a poor choice — far from it. Framer excels in its own right, particularly for designers and startups.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value incredibly easy to use for anyone, go with Canva. If beautiful design-first website builder matters more to you, Framer is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
